*διάκονος / diakonos / dee-ak'-on-os
=== Etymology ===

*Probably from [[διάκω]] diakō (obsolete, to run on errands; compare [[διώκω]] {{GG|1377}}); an attendant, that is, (generally) a waiter (at table or in other menial duties); specifically a Christian teacher and pastor (technically a deacon or deaconess): 
=== Noun ===
[[deacon]], [[minister]], [[servant]].